<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-power-model-trends-prep" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Power Model Trends Prep Activities</title>

  <investigation xml:id="pa-linear-trends-review">
    <introduction>
        <p>
            The table below shows the average price per pound ($/lb) of 100% beef ground chuck in the US in May<fn><url href="https://www.bls.gov/charts/consumer-price-index/consumer-price-index-average-price-data.htm" /></fn>
        </p>
        <table>
            <title>Average Price Per Pound ($/lb) of Ground Chuck in the US</title>
            <tabular halign="center" top="minor" bottom = "minor" right="minor" left="minor">
                <row header="yes">
                    <cell>Year</cell>
                    <cell>Price Per Pound</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>2006</cell>
                    <cell>2.508</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>2011</cell>
                    <cell>3.277</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>2016</cell>
                    <cell>3.902</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>2021</cell>
                    <cell>4.495</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>2026</cell>
                    <cell>6.718</cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>
    </introduction>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Sketch a graph showing this data. (Start by setting up axes! Do you need to include any negatives?)
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Find a formula for a linear model for this data. (If you're stuck, start by finding an average rate of change to use as your slope estimate. Then, ask yourself: what else do I need to finish this model?)
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Use your model to estimate the average cost of ground chuck in 2010. 
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The actual average cost in 2010 was $2.921/lb. How well did your model do?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Use your model to estimate when the average cost of ground chuck was $5/lb.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The actual average cost in 2022 was $4.894, in 2023 was $4.953, and in 2024 was $5.331. How well did you model do?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
  </investigation>

  <investigation xml:id="pa-review-exponential-trend">
    <introduction>
        <p>
            Although a linear model is a reasonable fit for the ground chuck cost data, an exponential model is better. Let's review finding and using exponential models.
        </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                First, we find the <m>\log_{10}</m> of the cost only. Use your calculator to fill in these values in the table below.
            </p>
            <table>
            <title>Average Price Per Pound ($/lb) of Ground Chuck in the US with Log($/lb)</title>
            <tabular halign="center" top="minor" bottom = "minor" right="minor" left="minor">
                <row header="yes">
                    <cell>Year</cell>
                    <cell>Price Per Pound</cell>
                    <cell>Log($/lb)</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>2006</cell>
                    <cell>2.508</cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>2011</cell>
                    <cell>3.277</cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>2016</cell>
                    <cell>3.902</cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>2021</cell>
                    <cell>4.495</cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>2026</cell>
                    <cell>6.718</cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Sketch a new graph that shows the years on the horizontal axis, and Log($/lb) on the vertical axis. This type of graph is sometimes called a <term>semi-log graph</term>, since one of the axes is the log of the data.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Find a linear model for Log($/lb) with respect to year. (If you're stuck, ask yourself: what information do I need in order to build a linear model?)
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Use your linear model for Log($/lb) to estimate <m>\log_{10}(\text{cost in 2010})</m>. Then, raise 10 to the power of your answer in order to get an estimate for the cost in 2010. How did this model do?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                In order to use this model to estimate when the cost of ground chuck was $5/lb, start by finding <m>\log_{10}(5).</m>. Then, plug <m>\log_{10}(5)</m> into the appropriate place in your model formula and use algebra to estimate the year. How did the model do on this estimate?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                In order to use this model to estimate the cost in a given year, we always have to raise 10 to the power of the output of our model. Sometimes, it's convenient to rewrite the model in exponential form, as
            </p>
            <me>
                C = 10^{mt + b}
            </me>
            <p>
                where <m>C</m> is the cost in $/lb and <m>mt + b</m> your linear model for Log($/lb). Write your model in this format.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
  </investigation>

  <investigation xml:id="pa-prep-survey-power-model-trends">
      <p>
          You'll need to be able to do the following things for this lesson. Rate how confident you are on a scale of 1 - 5 (1 = not confident and 5 = very confident).
      </p>
      <table>
          <tabular bottom = "minor" top = "minor" left = "minor" right = "minor">
              <row header ="yes" bottom = "minor">
                  <cell>Skill or Concept: I can …</cell>
                  <cell>Rating from 1 to 5</cell>
              </row>
              <row bottom = "minor">
                  <cell>Find a linear model for a data set that is only approximately linear.</cell>
                  <cell></cell>
              </row>
              <row bottom = "minor">
                  <cell>Use a calculator to find <m>\log_{10}</m> of a column of data.</cell>
                  <cell></cell>
              </row>
              <row bottom = "minor">
                <cell>Undo a <m>\log_{10}</m> by raising 10 to the power of a number.</cell>
                <cell></cell>
              </row>
          </tabular>
      </table>
  </investigation>
</section>